We‚Äôd want the best experts in the world to study the problem exhaustively, and we‚Äôd want their ideas filtered through the most advanced supercomputing to form empirical It‚Äôs a global issue, so we‚Äôd want global participation, collaborating, competing, offering nuanced judgments and checking each other‚Äôs We‚Äôd want to see whether past predictions had panned out and how accurately, all to narrow the cone of That‚Äôs exactly what has The world formed the IPCC to convene the best thinking from countries for the past thirty Their conclusions have been consistent and spot A good example is NASA‚Äôs predictions‚Äîthey have the best data set of any country, covering % of the globe and going back to the ‚Äîand their warnings have been astonishingly accurate to within degrees The IPCC‚Äôs consensus statements use words like unequivocal, unprecedented, % probability, severe and irreversible The conclusion is that the world must cut carbon emissions in half by , reaching net zero by , and that it‚Äôs If there is a better approach to believability, let‚Äôs hear Another framing is that this is the problem from hell because it features so many qualities that human psychology isn‚Äôt The list is long and We don‚Äôt do well with: , ambiguity, probability, selfishness, counterfactuals, uncertainty, invisibility, tribalism, and on and Well and true, but You could argue the very basis of central features in society like religion is to act in a way so as to be moral, altruistic and achieve distant future Same goes for Insurance is another cornerstone idea we readily accept to mitigate The odds of terrorists exploding a nuclear bomb that kills hundreds of thousands is roughly on the same order of magnitude as climate change, and we move heaven and earth to prevent A big part of civilization has always been to manage risk and complexity through investment and innovation, this is not an exotic Most people sense this is the When Pew asks citizens around the world whether climate change is a major, minor or not a threat, clear majorities across all advanced democracies say major, including In fact, all the opinion trendlines here at home are moving in the right direction, up big over the past five years, and up huge over the past Per Yale, majorities believe global warming is happening, believe it‚Äôs caused by humans, believe most experts are in agreement, believe it is personally important, believe they will be harmed, and are We also support a carbon tax if the proceeds go to environmental restoration or renewable energy R&D. Only one in seven think it‚Äôs too late to do something about The point is that skepticism is a bit of a The reason we feel that initial compulsion to figure it out is a lingering sense that there is contention on the And contention there is, if not so much on the merits as the The proportion of Americans who lean Democrat and believe climate change is a major threat has been in the percentiles in recent years, and has risen steadily, while those who lean Republican are in the and haven‚Äôt In an increasingly polarized society, so long as half the government is telling half the people to ignore an issue that is unknowable at the individual level, we‚Äôre going to have a It‚Äôs important to appreciate how unique what the GOP is doing They are the only major party among any advanced nation that is stonewalling on climate It‚Äôs not like they‚Äôre saying let‚Äôs do this but in the optimal way, they‚Äôre plugging their ears and not By doing so, and by taking measures such as pulling the world‚Äôs economic and technology leader out of the Paris Agreement, they subvert the consensus of the rest of the world‚Äîand in many aspects the future‚Äîso they may signal to their Republican constituency, which constitutes 1% of Why would they do that?
